          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Nuclear cooperation deal</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-17-2.png" alt="Nuclear cooperation deal" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Vietnam and Russia have signed an agreement to enhance cooperation in nuclear energy during Russian PM Mikhail Mishustin's visit to Hanoi. The deal reflects Vietnam's renewed interest in nuclear power after halting its nuclear projects in 2016 due to cost and safety concerns. Both sides supported the formation of comprehensive and sustainable structures for peace, stability, and economic integration collaborations through ASEAN, APEC, and other forums.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Russia has also given Vietnam the word that it will create favorable conditions for <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-01-2025-h2-2-vietnam-to-join-brics" target="_blank">Vietnam to join BRICS</a> in the future. Despite the offer, Vietnam remains cautious, with analysts citing concerns about U.S. reactions and limited immediate benefits from BRICS membership. Vietnam has mostly relied on the US ($111 billion) and China ($171 billion) for trade and arms supplies. Hanoi and Moscow have had diplomatic relations since 1950 and have been close allies since the Cold War.</p>
        </mj-text>
