          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">100-year deal</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">British Prime Minister Keir Starmer surprised Kyiv by visiting to sign a "100-Year Partnership" treaty with President Volodymyr Zelenskyy to strengthen security, science, energy, and trade ties. The agreement aims to boost military cooperation in the Baltic, Black, and Azov Seas to deter Russia. Starmer also announced nearly $48 million for Ukraine's post-war recovery. Britain says its 100-year pledge is part of assuring Ukraine that it will “never again be vulnerable to the kind of brutality inflicted on it by Russia.”</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">
          His visit highlights European solidarity amid concerns over reduced U.S. support under Donald Trump's "America First" policy. Part of the visit is to bolster UK support if the <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-01-2025-h3-3-reform-party-retakes-power" target="_blank">Reform Party retakes power</a>, as polls are putting them at a closer margin than last year. Nigel Farage, head of the party, has been skeptical about Ukraine’s war efforts and maintains the narrative that the West provoked Ukraine and that Ukraine should be willing to make concessions. Discussions included stationing Western troops in Ukraine to monitor a potential ceasefire.
</p>
        </mj-text>
    </mj-section>

