          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">
          <strong>🇮🇱 Israel PM grandstanding</strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Alon Pinkas, a former Israeli ambassador, is concerned about the hostage-ceasefire deal. He noted that while many Israelis are happy about the prospect of peace and hostages returning, there are doubts about whether the <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-01-2025-br1-ceasefire-will-hold" target="_blank">ceasefire will hold</a>. The Israeli cabinet pushed voting on it until today. Pinkas believes Netanyahu is using the situation to appease his extreme right-wing coalition partners, suggesting that the ceasefire may not hold and urging them not to leave the government. While many Israelis and Palestinians welcomed the deal, right-sign groups protested. There were also raids by the Israeli army in the West Bank on Thursday evening and more strikes on Gaza. On Friday morning, the Israeli PM office finally confirmed the deal.</p>
