          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">How did Romania and Bulgaria join the EU?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-17-3.png" alt="How did Romania and Bulgaria join the EU?" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Romania and Bulgaria became full members of the Schengen agreement this year. However, they <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-01-2025-f1-6-joining-the-european-union" target="_blank">joined the European Union</a> in 2007, so their entry to Schengen was quite late. 
           Both countries applied to join the EU in the 1990s, following the fall of communism. Like the rest of Central and Eastern Europe (CEE), they wanted to be more geopolitically aligned with the West.</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Both countries were given their accession negotiations in 2000. Both had to implement significant reforms to meet the EU's <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-01-2025-f2-7-political-economic-and-legal-criteria" target="_blank">political, economic, and legal criteria</a>, including strengthening democracy. Although both countries made progress, they faced challenges and were a little slower than their other CEE members counterparts who joined the bloc in 2004. Romania struggled with corruption, while Bulgaria had issues with its judiciary and rule of law. The EU monitored their progress closely, focusing on anti-corruption measures and judicial reforms.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Romania and Bulgaria satisfied the necessary reforms and were granted membership in the EU on January 1, 2007. While some say their progress was slower than initially planned, the EU set conditions for both countries to continue their reform processes. The EU established a monitoring mechanism to ensure they adhered to the agreed-upon reforms, particularly in corruption and judicial independence.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
